<font color="#FF0000">CHRISTMAS 1967</font><br>
<tt>Sat Dec 13  9:53:03 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I remember Christmas 1967<br><br>
We were recuperating after Operation foster, licking our wounds remembering our dead and just going on with our lives guarding Liberty Bridge. <br><br>
A numbness had set in over us. We no longer cared if you lived or died, it was all the same. Just time in the bush, America no longer seemed to exist in our minds, our lives was Vietnam.<br><br>
The NVA had already send us our Christmas Wreath, a nice arrangement of colorful ribbons, greenery, communist propaganda and signed by the Liberation Army. The notes attached offered a bounty on a our head according to our rank, some of us had been mentioned by name and we figured the only way the enemy would have obtained some of the information was from mama son who did our laundry.<br><br>
From the book, “Dreams of Glory, Clear Fields of Fire.” © Copyright 1997, Cook Barela.<br><br>
Late that afternoon (December 24th, 1967) while a new guy by the name of Cobbs was standing watch over Liberty Bridge he saw two large hand made Christmas wreathes floating down the Sung Tu Bon River. <br><br>
They were fished them out with caution because they might be booby trapped presents from the enemy. When we pulled them unto the bridge we found that, the wreathes were made from local foliage, large colorful  ribbons and banners. A nice hand written Christmas card was attached. The card had a hand drawn Christmas tree on its front and when you unfolded it, we read these words. <br><br>
Christmas Greetings;<br>
The National Liberation Force offers Holiday greetings, for Marines of India Company we offer, this bounty.<br><br>
For officers (sic) of  Marines <br>
lieutenant and higher 30,000 piasters<br>
Sergeants 20,000 piasters<br>
Corporal and lance Corporal 50,000 piasters<br>
these marines 200 piasters<br><br>
A list was enclosed with most of the current members of 1st and 2nd platoon Marines who over the past few months had been assigned to provide security at Liberty Bridge. It excluded the names of Marines who had been killed or wounded during operation Foster. <br><br>
The list of names that the NVA/VC used to compile the wanted list on the Christmas card list came from Marines that used the services of a Vietnamese women that came in weekly to pick up and deliver our laundry that was washed and laundered in DaNang. Some of the marines were angry that such a low amount had been offered for them. 200 was less then two dollars. But that was quite possibly the reaction that the NVA/VC had hoped to accomplish. To impose upon Marines a feeling of low worth and anger toward officers who did very little of the real fighting was another of the enemies war agaisnt us through psychological warfare.<br><br>
Marty had received a small Christmas tree from home and we had set it up in the hooch. Three large 50 cents in diameter size foot long lit candles, which were almost bigger then the tree decorated the background. <br><br>
Two boot bands held together a cut up c-rat box that I had used to wrap two brand new M-16 magazines for Marty, for Christmas. A note attached said<br>
 <br>
To: Marty;<br>
Do not open til Christmas, or if we get overrun.<br><br>
Next to it Marty had placed my Christmas present. <br><br>
A large can of gun oil and a brand new cleaning rod wrapped in some torn out pages from Playboy © the June 1967 issue.<br><br>
That night before retiring while Marty was pouring foot powder on his soaked and wrinkled feet, he took some of the white powdery stuff and sprinkled it on the little Christmas tree. <br><br>
“And a Merry Christmas to all and to all a Good Night he said,” and blew out the candle lights.<br><br>
December 25th<br>
As soon as 6:00 PM arrived the Christmas truce ended, and the platoon was helo-lifted out by a lone Chinook  helicopter and deposited back smack in the middle of Foster territory.<br><br>
Sparrowhawk<br>

